post_text:
A new survey to assess the needs of New Jersey residents during recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic has been created. Results will help to evaluate the tools, programs, and services that would be most beneficial as the public transitions. The survey is sponsored by the New Jersey Civic Community Recovery Committee (NJCCRC), a group of dedicated NJ library leaders whose mission is to work with stakeholders to create a new civic infrastructure that responds to this crisis with community-driven solutions (2020, para. 3).

Survey feedback will be used to leverage resources of New Jersey public libraries, in order to meet the needs of residents dealing with hardships during these difficult times.

Public libraries have always been among the greatest resources residents have in their community. Results of this survey will help adapt this vital role in the transitional phase into a post-pandemic environment.

Access the survey here: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSccZKK-NY_Vf9Qxu-zXF1dFgsIKGCsG85PArL4AmubYFwm21A/viewform

post_text: In 1986, the Department of Defense established April as Month of the Military Child, in order to underscore the important role children play in the Armed Forces community. There are approximately 2 million military children; 1.3 million of which are school-aged. Care of military children sustains our fighting force, and strengthens the health, security, and safety of our nation's families and communities. The color purple symbolizes all the branches of the military, as it is the combination of the five branches of the military service Army green, Marine red, Navy blue, Air Force blue and Coast Guard blue.

ATTENTION PARENTS/GUARDIANS: IMPORTANT INFORMATION FROM COLTS NECK POLICE - ROAD CLOSURES THAT COULD AFFECT DISMISSAL:

Hominy Hill Road (near #60) is completely closed due to a tree in the roadway on live power lines. We are actively working with JCP&L to resolve this. At this time there is no access to any roads off of Hominy Hill Road. This could possibly be in effect for at least an hour.

Rt 34 south bound near Highfield lane is closed due to a down tree and wires. Rt 34 north is open.

Heyersmill Road between Rt 537 and Merchants Way is also closed in both directions.

post_text:
A very special day on Wednesday for our lady scientists at CDMS thanks to their teacher, Mr. Marc Coe, who arranged for five guests, all female PhD students at NYU and CUNY, to have lunch with our students and share their research and experiences in their respective fields!

A very special thank you to our guests:

Carly Batist - studies lemur vocalizations in Madagascar. Is trying to decode and find the meaning in their language.

Katarina Evans & Megan Henriquez - studies baboon behavior and parasites in Ethiopia.

Emily Coco - archaeologist who studies human and neanderthal evolution in central Asia

Laura Newman - studies asocial behavior in male monkeys in Puerto Rico

And thank you to Mr. Coe for creating this wonderful experience!

Extra special thanks to our fabulous PTO for sponsoring this experience!

THIS SATURDAY, OCTOBER 26TH - 2-4 pm
TRUNK-OR-TREAT
Sponsored by the Colts Neck Twp. PTO

This is a great family event held at Bucks Mill Park, where children can trick-or-treat in a safe environment with their friends. Families decorate their trunks with spooky or silly Halloween décor and give out treats, as children walk from trunk to trunk filling their bags. Prizes are awarded to the best-decorated trunk. Come join us for a fun afternoon! To volunteer, please contact Justine Buzzetta at justinept@gmail.com or Joanne Passalacqua at joannepassalacqua@gmail.com.

One of today's stations for CDMS's Field Day was learning the popular dance, the Cupid Shuffle.
By doing so, the staff tried to not only teach dance moves but the idea that CDMS is a place where fun can be had, where you can "let loose" and be yourself, and that it's a safe place to learn without fear of being judged. At the end of the day, the entire school came together to dance and show off what they learned!

Well done CDMS!

Today was a very special day for 7th graders in Colts Neck.

It was a complete honor and privilege to host and share a meal with Holocaust survivors who shared their stories and messages of encouragement with our students.

A very sincere thank you to the Center for Holocaust, Human Rights, & Genocide Education (Chhange) for being such wonderful partners of our school community.

Truly inspiring

https://www.chhange.org/

post_text:
Continuing our celebration of our teachers during Teacher Appreciation Week 2019...

Every year, in addition to their time with students in their classrooms, Colts Neck teachers complete at least 15 hours of State mandated training; participate in hours of professional development sessions designed to enhance their practice, use student performance data to design Instruction, and discuss their curricular resources....

Another fact about Colts Neck teachers: In partnership with administration, our teachers are the DESIGNERS, EDITORS, and WRITERS of our curriculum and assessments. They transform New Jersey Learning Standards into LEARNING EXPERIENCES for Colts Neck students!

So much talent and knowledge!

post_text:
May is Mental Health Month! Small changes can make a big impact and the first step is education and breaking through stigmas about mental illness. Throughout the month of May, the green ribbon with the #breakthestigma that represents Mental Health Awareness will be the cover page photo for Colts Neck Township Schools.

According to a 2018 article published in Psychology Today, "...approximately one in five adults in the United States, 43.8 million, or 18.5%, experiences a mental illness in a given year and approximately one in five youth aged 13–18 (21.4%) experiences a severe mental health disorder at some point during their lifetime. For children aged 8–15, the estimate is 13%" (2018). These statistics are inclusive of depression and anxiety, the two most common forms of mental illness around the world.

This month, as part of our "whole child" approach to teaching & learning, Colts Neck Township Schools will facilitate a series of events and activities for students, staff, and families designed to support mental health and physical well-being. Stay tuned for more details!

post_text:
I am so excited to announce that Colts Neck Township Schools will be featured in the April 2019 edition of American School Boards Journal for being selected as a National School Boards Association 2019 Magna Award for Equity in Education 1st Place Winner!

The district is being recognized and celebrated for its M.O.V.E.S. and S.A.I.D. Programs that provide support services to students in the areas of physical therapy, speech therapy, and occupational therapy.

The district will be celebrated at the National School Boards Annual Conference in Philadelphia later this month. Colts Neck Township Schools is one of only five school districts, NATIONWIDE, to be selected as a first place winner in the category of 5,000 or less students.

We may be a small district, but the talent, passion, and commitment that our staff demonstrates EVERY DAY for children is larger than anything that can be imagined!

Way to go Colts Neck!!!!!!!

https://www.nsba.org/newsroom/press-releases/three-school-districts-earn-top-honors-2019-magna-awards-equity-programs

SUPER DUPER CONGRATULATIONS to 29 Conover Road Elementary School 5TH grade students who make up a total of 10 teams selected by a panel of external judges to move on to the NJSBA / US Army STEAM Tank Central Jersey Regional Competition scheduled for Saturday, March 16, 2019!

Special thanks and appreciation to our CRES Innovation Lab Teacher, Mrs. Michele Rogers, and District STEM Coach, Mr. Phil Capasso, for all of their efforts in working with all of our students throughout the submission process!

Oh, and did I mention...this is the first time Colts Neck has submitted projects for this awesome event? WELL DONE, COLTS NECK!!!!
